'''Ciar<U+00E1>n Mac Math<U+00FA>na''', (1925 <U+2013> 11 December 2009) was a former Irish broadcaster and music collector. He was a recognised authority on [[Irish music]] and lectured extensively on the subject. He travelled around Ireland, England, Scotland and America collecting music.<ref name="Legendary broadcaster Mac Math<U+00FA>na to retire"/>

According to [[Sam Smyth]] in the ''[[Irish Independent]]'', Mac Math<U+00FA>na was "on a mission to collect songs and stories, music, poetry and dance before they were buried under the coming tsunami of pop music".<ref name="Tributes flood in for veteran RTE broadcaster">{{cite web|author=[[Sam Smyth]]|url=http://www.independent.ie/national-news/tributes-flood-in-for-veteran-rte-broadcaster-1972467.html|title=Tributes flood in for veteran RTE broadcaster|date=2009-12-12|accessdate=2009-12-18|publisher=''[[Irish Independent]]''}}</ref> The broadcaster credited [[Sarah Keane|Sarah]] and [[Rita Keane]] with "keeping traditional music alive when it was at its lowest ebb".<ref name="Acclaimed traditional singer Rita Keane dies aged 86">{{cite web|author=Carl O'Brien|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/ireland/2009/0630/1224249782368.html|title=Acclaimed traditional singer Rita Keane dies aged 86|date=2009-06-30|accessdate=2009-12-11|publisher=''[[The Irish Times]]''|quote=RT<U+00C9> broadcaster and collector of traditional Irish music Ciar<U+00E1>n Mac Math<U+00FA>na has said the sisters played a crucial role in keeping traditional music alive when it was at its lowest ebb.}}</ref>

He presented ''[[Mo Cheol Th<U+00FA>]]'' for 35 years. Upon his retirement in 2005, MD of [[RT<U+00C9> Radio]] Adrian Moynes described Mac Math<U+00FA>na as "inseparable from RT<U+00C9> Radio".<ref name="Legendary broadcaster Mac Math<U+00FA>na to retire"/> Upon his deth in 2009, the ''[[Irish Independent]]'' described him as "a national treasure".<ref name="Thanks for the music, Ciaran">{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.ie/opinion/editorial/thanks-for-the-music-ciaran-1974076.html|title=Thanks for the music, Ciaran|date=2009-12-14|accessdate=2009-12-18|publisher=''[[Irish Independent]]''}}</ref>

==Early life and education==
Mac Math<U+00FA>na was born in [[Limerick]],<ref name="Broadcaster Ciar<U+00E1>n Mac Math<U+00FA>na dies"/> spending his early years in Mulgrave Street. He was schooled at [[C.B.S. Sexton Street|CBS Sexton St]], and later graduated from [[University College, Dublin]] with a [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]] in modern [[Irish language|Irish]] and [[Latin]].  Subsequently, he completed a [[Master of Arts (postgraduate)|MA]] in Irish.<ref name="times">''The Irish Times'', "BELOVED JOURNEYMAN", February 1, 1996</ref>

==Career==
After college Mac Math<U+00FA>na worked as a teacher and later at the Placenames Commission. In 1954, he joined [[RT<U+00C9> Radio 1|Radio <U+00C9>ireann]] where his job was to record [[Irish traditional music]]ians playing in their own locales.<ref name="times"/> This entailed visiting such places as [[Sliabh Luachra]], [[County Clare]] and [[County Sligo]], and the resulting recordings featured in his radio programmes: 
* ''Ceola  Tire''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iol.ie/~didly-didly/tradcent.html|author=Se<U+00E1>n Laffey|title=FROM VAUDEVILLE TO VIDEO|quote=His place in Ireland was taken by Ciar<U+00E1>n MacMathuna who presented Ceolta Tire and Job of Journey Work.|accessdate=18 December 2009}}</ref>
* ''A Job of Journeywork'' &mdash; listened to by [[Johnny McEvoy]]<ref name="He was Ireland's answer to Bob Dylan">{{cite web|author=Jackie Hayden|url=http://www.hotpress.com/archive/2760559.html|title=He was Ireland's answer to Bob Dylan|date=2004-10-26|accessdate=2009-12-11|publisher=''[[Hot Press]]''|quote=<U+201C>By the time I<U+2019>d got a job I was aware of The Clancy Brothers and used to listen to ''A Job Of Journeywork'', presented by Ciaran Mac Mathuna on Radio Eireann. But while on holidays in Blackpool, England one day I heard The Beatles<U+2019> <U+2018>Twist And Shout<U+2019> and I thought it was fabulous, so exciting. I still love it. So I became a fan of The Beatles, Buddy Holly, The Stones, The Everly Brothers too. I had a foot in both camps, the rock and roll and the folk, but there was Dylan to bridge the two.<U+201D>}}</ref>
* ''Humours of Donnybrook'' &mdash; [[Al O'Donnell]] and [[Luke Kelly]] performed a famous version of "[[On Raglan Road]]" on this show in 1979<ref name="Pioneer of Irish folk revival for The Crane">{{cite web|url=http://www.galwayindependent.com/entertainment/entertainment/pioneer-of-irish-folk-revival-for-the-crane/|title=Pioneer of Irish folk revival for The Crane|date=2009-01-28|accessdate=2009-12-11|publisher=''[[Galway Independent]]''}}</ref>

He would also be the person to interview future RT<U+00C9> Director General [[Cathal Goan]] when he sought a job at the broadcaster.<ref name="Broadcaster Mac Math<U+00FA>na taught us to treasure our music, poet tells mourners">{{cite web|author=Se<U+00E1>n Mac Connell|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/ireland/2009/1216/1224260761250.html|title=Broadcaster Mac Math<U+00FA>na taught us to treasure our music, poet tells mourners|date=2009-12-16|accessdate=2009-12-18|publisher=''[[The Irish Times]]''|quote=RT<U+00C9> director general Cathal Goan, who recalled being interviewed for his first job in the station by Ciar<U+00E1>n, said he had created a new hearth for the Irish people who listened to his programmes.}}</ref> Goan assisted in the organisation of Mac Math<U+00FA>na's music collection for the [[RT<U+00C9> Libraries and Archives]].<ref name="Tributes Paid To Ciar<U+00E1>n Mac Math<U+00FA>na">{{cite web|url=http://www.iftn.ie/broadcast/?act1=record&only=1&aid=73&rid=4282770&tpl=archnews&force=1|title=Tributes Paid To Ciar<U+00E1>n Mac Math<U+00FA>na|date=2009-12-14|accessdate=2009-12-18|publisher=[[Irish Film and Television Network]]|quote=RT<U+00C9> Director General Cathal Goan reflected that he owed a personal debt of gratitude to Ciar<U+00E1>n MacMath<U+00FA>na, who had given him his own introduction to Irish music. His first job in the RT<U+00C9> Archives had arisen through cataloguing the music and song collected by Ciar<U+00E1>n.}}</ref>

Mac Math<U+00FA>na's long-running Sunday morning radio series ''[[Mo Cheol Th<U+00FA>]]'' (You are my music) began in 1970 and continued until November 2005, when he retired from broadcasting.<ref name="Legendary broadcaster Mac Math<U+00FA>na to retire">{{cite web|url=http://www.rte.ie/arts/2005/1114/macmathunac.html|title=Legendary broadcaster Mac Math<U+00FA>na to retire|date=2005-11-14|accessdate=2009-12-11|publisher=[[Raidi<U+00F3> Teilif<U+00ED>s <U+00C9>ireann|RT<U+00C9>]]}}</ref><ref name="Broadcaster Ciar<U+00E1>n Mac Math<U+00FA>na dies"/> Each 45 minute programme offered a miscellany of archive music, poetry and folklore, mainly of Irish origin. It was one of radio's longest running programmes.<ref name="Legendary broadcaster Mac Math<U+00FA>na to retire"/><ref name="Broadcaster Ciar<U+00E1>n Mac Math<U+00FA>na dies"/> The last episode was broadcast on 27 November 2005 at 8.10 am.<ref name="Legendary broadcaster Mac Math<U+00FA>na to retire"/>

Mac Math<U+00FA>na won two [[Jacob's Awards]], in 1969 and 1990, for his [[RT<U+00C9> Radio 1|RT<U+00C9> Radio]] programmes promoting Irish traditional music.<ref name="Broadcaster Ciar<U+00E1>n Mac Math<U+00FA>na dies"/> He received the [[Freedom of the City|Freedom]] of [[Limerick City]] in June 2004.<ref name="Broadcaster Ciar<U+00E1>n Mac Math<U+00FA>na dies"/> He was also awarded honorary doctorates by [[NUI Galway]] and the [[University of Limerick]].<ref>''The Irish Times'', "'The thrill was in the pursuit of the tunes, as much as it was in their capture' ", November 26, 2005</ref> In 2007, he was awarded with the Musicians Award at the 10th annual [[TG4]] Traditional Music Awards.<ref name="CRAIC IS CEOL IN CORK WITH TG4 THIS EASTER">{{cite web|url=http://www.tg4.ie/bearla/corp/pr/2007/0322-1.asp|title=CRAIC IS CEOL IN CORK WITH TG4 THIS EASTER|date=2007-03-22|accessdate=2009-12-11|publisher=[[TG4]]}}</ref>

In 2002, a couple were successfully sued for "shattering the peace" in [[Blackrock, Dublin]] by playing Ciar<U+00E1>n Mac Math<U+00FA>na at excessive volumes early in the morning.<ref name="'Neighbours from hell' in court attempt to clear their name">{{cite web|author=Ray Managh|url=http://archives.tcm.ie/irishexaminer/2002/02/07/story22626.asp|title='Neighbours from hell' in court attempt to clear their name|date=2002-02-07|accessdate=2009-12-11|publisher=''[[Irish Examiner]]''}}</ref>

Joe Kennedy in the ''[[Sunday Independent]]'' in 2007 compared Mac Math<U+00FA>na to "an amiable rock, rolling gently along, still picking up some moss and morsels of music that he may have missed".<ref name="Travels with the last real balladeers">{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.ie/lifestyle/travels-with-the-last-real-balladeers-122602.html|title=Travels with the last real balladeers|date=2007-02-25|accessdate=2009-12-11|publisher=''[[Sunday Independent]]''}}</ref>

== Personal and later life ==
His wife Dolly MacMahon (using the English version of her surname) was a singer of traditional songs. She came from Galway and met her husband in 1955.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?gl=GB&v=zVTrW6_-2gc|title=Dolly MacMahon sings "Love is Pleasing"|accessdate=22 November 2009}}</ref> He had two sons named Padraic and Ciar<U+00E1>n, one daughter named D<U+00E9>irdre, and four grandchildren at the time of his death: Eoin, Colm, Conor and Liam.<ref name="Ciar<U+00E1>n MacMath<U+00FA>na's funeral Mass tomorrow">{{cite web|author=Kitty Holland|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/ireland/2009/1214/1224260655243.html|title=Ciar<U+00E1>n MacMath<U+00FA>na's funeral Mass tomorrow|date=2009-12-14|accessdate=2009-12-18|publisher=''[[The Irish Times]]''|quote=He is survived by his widow Dolly, sons Padraic, Ciar<U+00E1>n and daughter D<U+00E9>irdre, and grandchildren Eoin, Colm, Conor and Liam.}}</ref>

He died on 11 December 2009.<ref name="Broadcaster Ciar<U+00E1>n Mac Math<U+00FA>na dies">{{cite web|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2009/1211/macmathuna.html|title=Broadcaster Ciar<U+00E1>n Mac Math<U+00FA>na dies|date=2009-12-11|accessdate=2009-12-11|publisher=[[RT<U+00C9> News and Current Affairs]]}}</ref><ref name="Former broadcaster Ciaran MacMath<U+00FA>na dies">{{cite web|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/breaking/2009/1211/breaking70.htm|title=Former broadcaster Ciaran MacMath<U+00FA>na dies|date=2009-12-11|accessdate=2009-12-11|publisher=''[[The Irish Times]]''}}</ref><ref name="Broadcaster Ciar<U+00E1>n Mac Math<U+00FA>na has died">{{cite web|url=http://www.rte.ie/arts/2009/1211/macmathunac.html|title=Broadcaster Ciar<U+00E1>n Mac Math<U+00FA>na dies|date=2009-12-11|accessdate=2009-12-11|publisher=[[Raidi<U+00F3> Teilif<U+00ED>s <U+00C9>ireann|RT<U+00C9>]]}}</ref>

[[Taoiseach]] [[Brian Cowen]] paid tribute, saying: <U+201C>He was encyclopaedic in his knowledge of Irish traditional music and its artists and for many many decades, wherever good Irish music was played and enjoyed, Ciar<U+00E1>n was to be found in its midst<U+201D>.<ref name="Former broadcaster Ciaran MacMath<U+00FA>na dies"/> [[Minister for Arts, Sport and Tourism (Ireland)|Minister for Arts, Sport and Tourism]] [[Martin Cullen]] described Mac Math<U+00FA>na as "a man of great intellect with a wonderful commitment to and understanding of Irish folklore and the traditional arts".<ref name="Ciar<U+00E1>n MacMath<U+00FA>na dies"/> [[Niall Stokes]], editor of ''[[Hot Press]]'', spoke of being "in the process of losing a great generation of Irish folk pioneers" &mdash; musician [[Liam Clancy]] had died just days previously &mdash; and called for a "[continuation of] justice to the extraordinary work they did in reviving the true spirit of Irish folk and traditional music and re-instating it at the heart of the Irish experience [...] in our public policy, and in particular our broadcasting framework".<ref name="Ciar<U+00E1>n MacMath<U+00FA>na dies">{{cite web|url=http://www.hotpress.com/Ciar%E1n%20MacMath%FAna/news/Ciarn-MacMathna-dies/6098336.html|title=Ciar<U+00E1>n MacMath<U+00FA>na dies|date=2009-12-12|accessdate=2009-12-12|publisher=''[[Hot Press]]''|quote='''Full statements from Niall Stokes and Martin Cullen''': "Coming hard on the heels of the death of Liam Clancy, the passing of Ciar<U+00E1>n MacMath<U+00FA>na is a signal that we are in the process of losing a great generation of Irish folk pioneers," ''Hot Press'' editor Niall Stokes said. "Let us hope that, in our public policy, and in particular our broadcasting framework, we continue to do justice to the extraordinary work they did in reviving the true spirit of Irish folk and traditional music and re-instating it at the heart of the Irish experience." [...] The Minister for the Arts, Martin Cullen, aIso paid tribute: "I was saddened to hear of the passing of the distinguished Irish broadcaster, Ciar<U+00E1>n Mac Math<U+00FA>na who contributed so much to the cultural life of this country, not only through his television and radio career with RT<U+00C9> but also as a collector of Irish music, poetry and song. A man of great intellect with a wonderful commitment to and understanding of Irish folklore and the traditional arts, Ciar<U+00E1>n made it a priority over the course of his long life to travel and meet musicians and to collect Irish music and stories, preserving them for future generations. He has left us with a wonderful legacy. An accomplished producer and presenter for RT<U+00C9>, he will be best remembered for his Sunday morning radio programme ''Mo Cheol Th<U+00FA>'' where his wisdom and love of Irish music and the written word shone through. Ciar<U+00E1>n Mac Math<U+00FA>na was widely admired and deeply respected and appreciated by all who knew him. My sincere sympathy is extended to his wife Dolly McMahon and their three children and extended family at this time."}}</ref> A billboard advertisement for ''Mo Cheol Th<U+00FA>'' with the caption <U+201C>The Touch of the Master<U+2019>s Hand<U+2019><U+2019> was positioned in [[Terenure College Chapel]] where his corpse was carried.<ref name="Praise at removal for 'a gentle person'">{{cite web|author=Michael O'Regan|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/ireland/2009/1215/1224260713554.html|title=Praise at removal for 'a gentle person'|date=2009-12-15|accessdate=2009-12-18|publisher=''[[The Irish Times]]''|quote=An RT<U+00C9> billboard advertising one of his long-running radio programmes, ''Mo Cheo Thu'', and bearing the inscription <U+201C>The Touch of the Master<U+2019>s Hand<U+2019><U+2019>, was placed in the foyer of the church.}}</ref><ref name="Old friends pay respects to Mac Mathuna">{{cite web|author=[[Sam Smyth]]|url=http://www.independent.ie/national-news/old-friends-pay-respects-to-mac-mathuna-1975114.html|title=Old friends pay respects to Mac Mathuna|date=2009-12-15|accessdate=2009-12-18|publisher=''[[Irish Independent]]''}}</ref>

Mac Math<U+00FA>na's funeral on 15 December 2009 was attended by hundreds of people, including aides-de-camp of the President and Taoiseach, RT<U+00C9> Director General [[Cathal Goan]], poet [[S<U+00E9>amus Heaney]] and others.<ref name="Hundreds attend Mac Math<U+00FA>na funeral"/><ref name="Funeral of broadcaster takes place">{{cite web|author=Se<U+00E1>n Mac Connell|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/breaking/2009/1215/breaking69.htm|title=Funeral of broadcaster takes place|date=2009-12-15|accessdate=2009-12-18|publisher=''[[The Irish Times]]''}}</ref> Heaney said at the funeral: <blockquote>Over a lifetime he helped the population of Ireland to realise the beauty, strength and value of their native cultural possessions, above all their musical culture. The musical instrument which Ciaran played to magical effect, and which entranced generations of listeners, was his own voice.<ref name="'It was such a shame he wasn't here, he missed a great funeral'">{{cite web|author=Jason O'Brien|url=http://www.independent.ie/national-news/it-was-such-a-shame-he-wasnt-here-he-missed-a-great-funeral-1976562.html|title='It was such a shame he wasn't here, he missed a great funeral'|date=2009-12-16|accessdate=2009-12-18|publisher=''[[Irish Independent]]''}}</ref></blockquote> Musicians to perform at the ceremony included [[Peadar <U+00D3> R<U+00ED>ada]], [[C<U+00F3>r C<U+00FA>il Aodha]] and members of [[The Chieftains]] and [[Planxty]].<ref name="Hundreds attend Mac Math<U+00FA>na funeral"/> The corpse was then taken to Mount Jerome Crematorium.<ref name="Hundreds attend Mac Math<U+00FA>na funeral">{{cite web|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2009/1215/macmathuna.html|title=Hundreds attend Mac Math<U+00FA>na funeral|date=2009-12-15|accessdate=2009-12-18|publisher=[[RT<U+00C9> News and Current Affairs]]}}</ref>


Journalist [[Kevin Myers]] said Mac Math<U+00FA>na's legacy would be the "rebirth of Irish music", adding: <blockquote>Well, if Ciar<U+00E1>n Mac Math<U+00FA>na can die, I suppose anyone can. Actually, I had always thought that he was immortal. He certainly appeared to have all the ingredients.<ref name="Kevin Myers: The rebirth of Irish music is Ciaran Mac Mathuna's legacy">{{cite web|author=[[Kevin Myers]]|url=http://www.independent.ie/opinion/columnists/kevin-myers/kevin-myers-the-rebirth-of-irish-music-is-ciaran-mac-mathunas-legacy-1975179.html|title=Kevin Myers: The rebirth of Irish music is Ciaran Mac Mathuna's legacy|date=2009-12-15|accessdate=2009-12-18|publisher=''[[Irish Independent]]''}}</ref></blockquote>

